            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
            "segment": "Why Angular Momentum Can Never Point",
            "greeting": "Salut, Liam",
            "runningText": "explaining the mechanism\u2026",
            "output": [],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/NBB00.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 9.0,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-NBB00.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.68
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "t_start": 0.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9.0,
      "narration_text": "Take a quantum spinning object and align it as perfectly as the rules allow. The angular momentum still refuses to point straight up.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.84,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "t_start": 9.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9.0,
      "narration_text": "Set it to the maximum allowed orientation. The z-component reaches its ceiling. And the vector still leans \u2014 sweeping a cone around the axis, never lining up.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.03,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "t_start": 18.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10.0,
      "narration_text": "The total length is hbar times root-ell-times-ell-plus-one. The biggest z-shadow is just ell-hbar. Those two numbers are never equal \u2014 so the vector can never line up with the axis.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "kind": "question",
        "copy": "Total: hbar sqrt(ell(ell+1))   Max z: ell*hbar   Why are they never equal?"
      },
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.36,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "t_start": 28.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11.0,
      "narration_text": "Classical intuition says angular momentum is just a spinning arrow. Point it wherever you like. A gyroscope can line up with the z-axis exactly. Why can't a quantum system?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.53,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "t_start": 39.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10.0,
      "narration_text": "Even quantum mechanics seems to allow it. You can measure the z-component and get a sharp value. That looks like pointing along the axis.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.78,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "t_start": 49.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12.0,
      "narration_text": "But here is the constraint the algebra enforces. The total squared magnitude equals L-x squared plus L-y squared plus L-z squared. Every term is a square \u2014 so every term is non-negative.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.52,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "t_start": 61.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12.0,
      "narration_text": "For the vector to point straight up, both sideways components would need to be exactly zero. But in any state with a definite z-component, the sideways components carry unavoidable spread \u2014 quantum uncertainty forces them off zero.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.29,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "t_start": 73.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11.0,
      "narration_text": "So the total length is always strictly bigger than the z-shadow. The gap is hbar times root-ell \u2014 that is the mandatory sideways contribution. No state can shrink it to zero.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.68,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "t_start": 84.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10.0,
      "narration_text": "The cone half-angle \u2014 the lean off the axis \u2014 is the arccosine of ell over root-ell-times-ell-plus-one. For ell equals two, that is about 35 degrees. As ell grows, the angle shrinks.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "kenburns",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "The cone half-angle \u2014 the lean off the axis \u2014 is\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "THE MECHANISM",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B09.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "scene_description": "A cone diagram: a z-axis vertical, an angular momentum vector of fixed length sweeping around the cone, its shadow projection shorter than the vector, labeled with the cone half-angle",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.04,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "t_start": 94.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11.0,
      "narration_text": "Take ell very large \u2014 a thousand, a million. The angle collapses nearly to zero. The cone narrows to a thread. In the limit, the quantum rule recovers the classical arrow.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "rotate"
      },
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.31,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "t_start": 105.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11.0,
      "narration_text": "This is not a measurement disturbance. The x and y components have no definite value \u2014 the angular momentum simply does not have a well-defined direction in space.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.33,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B11.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B11.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "t_start": 116.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 13.0,
      "narration_text": "A student works out the ell-equals-two top state. Total length is hbar root-six \u2014 about 2.45 hbar. Maximum z-shadow is 2 hbar. She draws the cone: half-angle 35 degrees, still leaning, even at maximum alignment.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "act": "THE EXAMPLE",
      "example_note": "illustrative \u2014 numbers from the ell=2 spectrum",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 16.33,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B12.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B12.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "t_start": 129.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11.0,
      "narration_text": "She tries ell equals ten. Cone half-angle drops to about 18 degrees. Still not zero. Only at ell equals infinity does the quantum arrow finally straighten.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "act": "THE EXAMPLE",
      "example_note": "illustrative",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.95,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B13.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B13.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "t_start": 140.0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10.0,
      "narration_text": "Why can quantum angular momentum never point straight up? Because the total magnitude is always strictly larger than the maximum z-projection \u2014 the sideways spread cannot be zero.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "card": {
        "kind": "endcard",
        "copy": "hbar sqrt(ell(ell+1)) > ell*hbar \u2014 always. The cone never closes.",
        "kicker": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
      },
      "act": "RECAP",
      "audio_file": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B14.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.567,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/clips/B14.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-angular-momentum-cone/mp3/beat-B14.mp3"
    },
